Player

Your second term was about to begin.

Narrator

A year later, Remus started seizing the assets of Bludish businesses. Many businessmen were arrested under charges of corruption.\n\nHe also promoted the idea of "Maroon Blood" and heavily invested in eugenic research and the military. He openly supported and funded the Young Sords.

1958

Player

You protested against the policies.

Narrator

You dreamed about the future. You saw a wealthier Sordland.\n\nThe country saw massive economic development over your next term. The remnants of the Soll era were long gone, businesses became more profitable and the markets were freed of regulation.\n\nAs the market became freer, the people of Sordland also became free. As the economic boom continued, the most critical problems vanished one by one. Sordland was finally letting go of its past.

Narrator

You dreamed about the future. You saw a Sordland of self-reliant greatness.\n\nThe country saw massive social and economic reforms over your term. The state became stronger and provided the highest-quality services to its people with strides made towards autarky.\n\nSordland was finally embracing its true self. As the state became richer, the people earned comfort. You made Sordland even stronger than it was before.

Player

You worked to achieve the dream of Malenyev.

Narrator

With a sense of duty to your nation, you worked hard, sacrificing all of your time, your sleep, even your soul.\n\nThanks to your efforts, Sordland became stronger and a better place to live for its citizens -- and you. You heard them cheer your name.\n\nYou smiled. You knew you deserved to be praised more than anyone for the success.

Narrator

Your support buoyed Monica to new heights. People began referring to you as "Monica Rayne's husband."

Narrator

You and Monica began speaking to each other again, although she refused to consider getting back together.

Player

You never talked to Monica again.

Narrator

A year later, Lileas launched a massive campaign to rewrite the constitution of Sordland. \n\nHer proposal was aimed at strengthening the executive and judiciary branches, while transforming the election system so that the next president would be chosen by specific electors rather than the popular vote.\n\nShe offered you the position of Vice President in exchange for your support.

1961

Narrator

A year later, Manoly launched a massive campaign to rewrite the constitution of Sordland. \n\nHer proposal was aimed at strengthening the legislative branch, and expanding the rights of women and minorities, and eliminating the unequal distribution of campaign funding.\n\nShe offered you the position of Vice President in exchange for your support.

1961

Narrator

A year later, Remus launched a massive campaign to rewrite the constitution of Sordland. \n\nHis proposal aimed to strengthen presidential powers, abolish the citizenship of Bludish people and implement racial laws to segregate the others from the "Maroon Bloods."\n\nHe offered you the position of Vice President in exchange for your support.

1961

Narrator

A year later, Leke and Stahler launched a massive campaign to rewrite the constitution of Sordland. \n\nTheir proposal aimed to strengthen the legislative branch, expand the rights of women and minorities, and ensure that the means of production would be owned by the workers.\n\nHe offered you the position of Interior Minister in exchange for your support.

1961

Player

Player

Narrator

Unfortunately, the proposal did not pass the Assembly. The resources invested in the campaign made the party fall victim to internal strife.\n\nEach faction put forth their own candidates against the president. A congress to elect the party leadership was on the horizon.\n\nYou...

Narrator

You announced that you were running for leadership, becoming the eighth candidate in the NFP Congress.\n\nUnfortunately, you lost the vote to Kesaro Kibener. The following month, he stripped you of your membership and forced you out of the party.\n\nYou decided that it was time for you to retire from politics. You continued your service as an independent MP until the end of your term and did not run for re-election.

Narrator

For the inauguration, you stood on the podium next to the party leader overlooking the famous Hill of Pride. The new cabinet was ready to serve the country. It was a particularly cold day.\n\nWhen you looked at the thousands of people with hopeful eyes, your shoulders grew heavy and you shivered. \n\nYou were going to be their next Vice President.

1962|January 18th

Narrator

With no clear leadership, the People's Freedom and Justice Party failed at entering the Assembly while the National Front Party became the second largest by a number of seats.

Narrator

With no clear leadership, the National Front Party failed at entering the Assembly while the People's Freedom and Justice Party became the second largest by number of seats.

Narrator

The National Front Party came in second; without any clear leadership, the PFJP limped into third. This time, however, the Communist Party of Sordland also managed to enter the Assembly as the fourth largest party.

Narrator

The last thing you remembered was chaos. The people in the crowd screamed and scrambled for cover as security chased after the gunman. \n\nYour guards rushed to your side, but it was too late. You'd been hit. You collapsed to the ground, and everything faded to black.

Narrator

The last thing you remembered was a shout of "For Free Bludia! Yollak Bluderat!" -- and then, chaos. The people in the crowd screamed and scrambled for cover as security chased after the gunman. \n\nYour guards rushed to your side, but it was too late. You'd been hit. You collapsed to the ground, and everything faded to black.

Narrator

You made a full recovery just in time for election day. Millions went out to cast their votes, setting turnout records in Sordland.
